    "summary": "The conversion of Poland to Christianity (966 AD) under Duke Mieszko I of the Piast dynasty was the founding act of the Polish state and its integration into Western European Christian civilization — a decision with political implications as profound as its religious ones. Mieszko I's baptism (966 AD) and marriage to Dobrawa, a Czech (Bohemian) princess, was motivated partly by genuine religious interest but largely by political calculation: converting to Latin Christianity put Poland under papal protection, gave it equal status with the German Holy Roman Empire's princes (rather than remaining a target for 'missionary' conquest), and aligned it with a sophisticated administrative and diplomatic tradition.\n\nPoland's conversion followed the Latin (Western) rather than Greek (Eastern) Orthodox rite — a choice that placed it firmly in the Western cultural sphere and created the lasting boundary between Catholic Poland and Orthodox Russia/Ukraine that has shaped Eastern European religious and cultural geography ever since. Within a generation, the first Polish bishop was established (at Poznan, 968 AD), and under Mieszko's son Boleslaw I the Brave (r. 992–1025 AD), Poland became a major European power recognized as a kingdom by the Holy See and the Holy Roman Emperor. The 966 conversion is commemorated as the founding date of the Polish state — 'Poland's Baptism' — and is perhaps the single most important date in Polish national history. Poland's Catholic identity has been a central element of Polish national consciousness ever since.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Christianization_of_Poland",
